the particles ol any substance when effervescing in un· confined air are so much pressed by the weight and pressure ol the incumbent atmosphere that they can- not expand freely 3 while yet the same particles, being scarcely burdened at· all in a place void ol air, will in performing their movements spread out and swell up much more : but this does not come from their more intense action and motion, but from the removal ol the hindrance. And hence it is that if water slightly warmed be put in a place void os air, its more agile particles will make the liquid swell and as it were hoil, and yet it is not to be supposed that these particles are agitated with a greater force than before. So that clearly, even if the fermentation ola mixture os con- trary liquids in a vacuum were to go on with less force than in free air, still their fermenting particles would spread out toa greater extent than otherwise owing to the withdrawal of the pressure of the atmosphere. , To this I add that contrary salts‚ if mixed together in a vacuum and then quickly removed alter eller- vescence has gone on for some time, do not appear to have been heated as much as in other circumstances. So that it would appear that even the heat ol contrary salts fermenting together, depends to some extent on nitro-aerial particlcs struck out from the air, as we have already hinted.

It is besides to be noted that there is a great difference between the fermentation of the blood and that of contrary salts‚ inasmuch as the effervescence of the latter is due to an internal principle, namely to nitro-aerial particles contained in them, as I already endeavoured to show, while the fermentation of the blood is excited by the nitro-a'e'rial spirit supplied by the air meeting its saline-sulphureous particles.
